Essential Git Commands for DevOps Engineers

ğŸ”§ Setup & Configuration
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"
git config --list     ïƒ¨Verify configuration

ğŸ“¥ Repository Management
git init               				ïƒ¨Initialize a new Git repo
git init <repo name>             		ïƒ¨ create an initialized empty git repo
git clone <repo-url>               		ïƒ¨Clone an existing repo
git remote -v               			ïƒ¨View configured remote repos
git remote add <link of remote empty repository>

ğŸ“„ Working with Files
git status               			ïƒ¨Show modified, staged, and untracked files
git add <file>               			ïƒ¨Stage a specific file
git add .               			ïƒ¨Stage all changes
git rm <file>               			ïƒ¨Remove file from staging and disk
git rm -rf <file/folder name>   		ïƒ¨forcefully remove
git mv <old> <new>               		ïƒ¨Rename or move file

ğŸ’¾ Committing Changes
git commit -m "Your message"               ïƒ¨Commit staged changes
git commit -am "msg"               		ïƒ¨Add & commit tracked files in one step

ğŸ•— Viewing History
git log               				ïƒ¨View commit history
git log --oneline --graph --all               ïƒ¨Compact, visual commit tree
git diff               				ïƒ¨View unstaged changes
git diff --staged               			ïƒ¨View staged changes


ğŸ” Branching & Merging [a merge after rebase will become ff merge kind of rebase so use --no-ff]
git branch               	ïƒ¨List branches
git branch -r 		ïƒ¨ list remote branches
git branch -a 		ïƒ¨ list all local and remote
git branch <name>               ïƒ¨Create a new branch
git branch -m <new name>      ïƒ¨ rename the branch
git branch -d <branch name>	ïƒ¨ delete the branch
git checkout <branch>               ïƒ¨Switch branches
git checkout -b <name>               ïƒ¨Create & switch to new branch
git merge <branch>               	ïƒ¨Merge branch into current
git merge --ff-only <branch>      ïƒ¨ fast forward merge which is basically a rebase
git merge --no-ff <branch>      ïƒ¨ forced merge which is basic without ff
git rebase <branch>               ïƒ¨Reapply commits on top of another base
git merge/rebase --abort      ïƒ¨ unmerge or unbase

â˜ï¸ Remote Collaboration
git pull               			ïƒ¨Fetch + merge changes from remote
git fetch               		ïƒ¨Only download changes
git push               		ïƒ¨Upload changes to remote
git push -u origin <branch>               ïƒ¨Push new branch to remote & track

âœ… 1. Undo Working Directory Changes
Task	Command
Discard changes in a file	git restore <file>
Discard all changes	git restore .
Discard and unstage	git restore --staged <file> + git restore <file>
Discard new (untracked) files	git clean -f
Discard new untracked directories	git clean -fd
Preview what clean will delete	git clean -n

âœ… 2. Undo Staging (Unstage Files)
Task	Command
Unstage a specific file	git reset <file>
Unstage all files	git reset
Unstage and keep changes	git restore --staged <file>

âœ… 3. Undo Commits
Task	Command
Undo the last commit but keep changes	git reset --soft HEAD~1
Undo last commit and unstage changes	git reset --mixed HEAD~1
Undo last commit and discard changes	git reset --hard HEAD~1
Undo multiple commits	git reset --hard HEAD~N
Revert a commit (safe, creates new commit)	git revert <commit_hash>

âœ… 4. Clean Untracked Files
Task	Command
List what will be deleted	git clean -n
Delete untracked files	git clean -f
Delete untracked files and dirs	git clean -fd
Delete ignored files too	git clean -fx
Clean everything: untracked, dirs, ignored	git clean -fdx

âœ… 5. Stash Changes (Temporary Undo)
Task	Command
Save uncommitted changes	git stash
View stashes	git stash list
Apply last stash	git stash apply
Apply and delete stash	git stash pop
Drop a stash	git stash drop stash@{0}
Clear all stashes	git stash clear

ğŸš¨ Warnings
â€¢	git reset --hard and git clean permanently delete changes. Use with caution.
â€¢	Use git status a

ğŸ› ï¸ Stashing & Cherry-picking
git stash               		ïƒ¨Save work temporarily
git stash pop               		ïƒ¨Re-apply stashed changes
git cherry-pick <commit>               ïƒ¨Apply a specific commit

ğŸ” Debugging & Auditing
git blame <file>               	ïƒ¨Show who changed what
git show <commit>               	ïƒ¨Show changes of a commit
git bisect               		ïƒ¨Find commit that introduced a bug
